[normal]Written evidence s[bold]ubmitted by the Centre for Low Carbon Futures[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Summary[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Responses t[bold]o questions[bold]Q1. Will the Government's current approach towards low carbon innovation help to achieve the UK's legally binding targets at the lowest possible cost?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q2. Does the Government have the right balance of focus between 
[normal]energy efficiency, renewable energy and other low carbon technologies?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q3. What 
[normal]outcomes, if any, are the LCICG likely to achieve? How should its forthcoming strategy drive more investment into low carbon innovation, and how should it measure success?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q4. Are the Government &amp; LCICG targeting investment towards the most effe
[normal]ctive stages of the innovation process, including over the long-term?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q5. What is the impact of the short-term funding timelines on private sector investment?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q6. How should DECC ensure that its remaining capital allocation for low carbon innovation will be spent wisely, after two years of underspend?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q7. How is the Government maximising opportunities to learn from and partner with internationa
[normal]l partners within and beyond the EU?
[normal]December 2013
